1211A - Three Problems
Just choose any three indices with different values and print them in order of increasing values. You can do it in a billion ways. One of the is to use map data structure (from elements to indices): while reading the data assign value $$$i$$$ for the key $$$a_i$$$ (use an ordered map, for example, TreeMap). If the size of the map less than $$$3$$$, print
-1
. Overwise print values (i.e. correspondent values) for the first three elements of the map.
Here is the example of a solution in Kotlin:
fun main() {
val n = readLine()!!.toInt()
val r = readLine()!!.split(" ").map { it.toInt() }
.withIndex()
.distinctBy { it.value }
.sortedBy { it.value }
.map { it.index + 1 }
if (r.size < 3) {
println("-1 -1 -1")
} else {
println("${r[0]} ${r[1]} ${r[2]}")
}
}
